* Prefer text interfaces to graphical interfaces
  * Graphical User Interfaces (GUIs) can be helpful, but they should be _interfaces_, not bottlenecks: the underlying process should exist separately from the interface
    * The GUI needs to be aware of the data, but the data shouldn't need to be aware of the GUI
    * Interaction with a GUI is not generally conducive to reproducibility, so even when it is used, processes should be recorded in text artifacts that are both human and machine readable
    * This facilitates automation, reproducibility, interoperability, and transparency
    * The GUI should not hold the user "captive"
* Prefer keyboard interaction to mouse interaction
  * Ten fingers can do more than a single cursor
  * Mouse interaction makes visual search a cognitive bottleneck, and every point and click interface is organized differently
* Prefer local interaction to remote interaction when possible
